flowPara.flowSpan: Stability Analysis of Boolean Network Reduction
According to the Determinative Power of

text.tspan: Boolean networks feature nodes limited to binary values such as 0 and
1, on and off, or true and false, and connected according to some set of
logical rules. Boolean models have been employed in areas such as
genetic regulatory systems, neural networks, and telecommunications
systems, and researchers from many disciplines have adopted Boolean
approaches to approximate the behavior of complex systems.
Despite their simplified structure, Boolean models can be
computationally burdensome when they have a large number of nodes.
Much of the recent research into Boolean networks investigates
potential network reduction techniques. One strategy, explored here,
aims to identify and preserve important nodes while eliminating those
with little impact on network behavior.
Network reduction is attractive because every time a node is removed,
the total state space is halved. If any particular node does not have a
significant impact, the computational advantages of its elimination might

tspan.tspan: outweigh the drawbacks of reduced model

text.tspan: The stability of a network describes the presence of patterned behavior

tspan.tspan: over many iterations. If a network exhibits periodic orbits or frozen
. If no patterns emerge, the network is

text.tspan: Derrida plots illustrate stability using Hamming distance, H(t), which
represents the number of nodes with opposite values in two parallel
networks evolved from different initial states. The plots relate H(t) on the
x-axis with H(t+1), the distance after iteration of the initial states, on the
y-axis. If points tend to lie below the diagonal (see Figure 1), the network
shows order. If more observations lie above the diagonal (Figure 2), the

tspan.tspan: network is chaotic. A proliferation of points along the diagonal indicates
that the network operates in the critical phase.

text.tspan: For a subnetwork to serve as a useful approximation of its parent , it
should have similar stability characteristics. For example, any chaotic
subnetwork of a highly-ordered parent has changed meaningfully
during the reduction process. Accordingly, insights gleaned from analysis

tspan.tspan: of the subnetwork might be limited in their applicability to the parent.

text.tspan: To assess the utility of determinative-power-based reduction, we can
compare subnetworks and their parents in terms of various aspects of

tspan.tspan: dynamics. Here, we examine the extent to which reduction impacts
the stability of the resulting subnetwork.

text.tspan: We put theory in practice by developing a reduction algorithm, testing it on

tspan.tspan: 36 network types, and examining how the stability of resulting subnetworks
relates to that of their parent networks.

text.tspan: The 36 network types simulated represent combinations of four functions,
three connectivities, and three wiring distributions. We include two
threshold functions (0.25 and 0.5) and two canalyzing functions (depths 1
and 2). The selected k-values are 2, 3, and 4, and the wiring distributions are
uniform, Poisson, and power law. See Table 1 for details. Computational
limitations restrict the number of choices for each setting as each option

tspan.tspan: doubles the total number of simulations.
The network reduction algorithm implemented here relies upon

text.tspan: determinative power. The precise calculation of determinative power
uses the concepts of Shannon entropy and conditional entropy, both of
which have applications beyond network modeling.
To define Shannon entropy (H), consider X a discrete random variable
and p(x) = P(X = x) its probability mass function. In a Boolean context,
X can represent any node in the network and can take values of 0 or 1.

text.tspan: We implement the determinative-power-based reduction algorithm on each

tspan.tspan: network type and seek patterns. For each type, we randomly generate 100

text.tspan: networks with the desired settings, find average values, and compare across

tspan.tspan: all three dimensions (connectivity, topology distribution, and functionality).
In each simulation, we find the average ratio

text.tspan: of initial conditions for the parent network and all subnetworks. This ratio
provides an estimate for the stability of the network. Ratios greater than 1
suggests chaotic behavior, those less than 1 indicates order, and those near 1

tspan.tspan: place the network in the critical phase. To relate subnetwork stability to
that of the parent, we generate a ratio of ratios:

text.tspan: Lower values of this ratio suggest that the subnetwork is more ordered than
the parent. Figures 3-6 illustrate how subnetwork size impacts ratio values.
Most of the curves share a similar shape: concave decreasing for the first 50
or so reductions. This indicates that for most network types, reductions lead
to an increase in order but that the impact is limited in the initial reductions,
which eliminate nodes with the smallest determinative power.
The most distinct curve shapes are those associated with threshold = 0.25
functions, higher k-values, and uniform-and Poisson-distributed topologies.
In these cases, subnetworks between n = 75 and n = 25 are more chaotic
than their parents.
The plots reveal general trends in how settings impact the performance of
DP-based reduction. Networks with connectivity of k = 2 tend to have lower
ratios, suggesting that reductions quickly lead to more highly ordered
behavior. In regards to functionality, ratios associated with a 0.5 threshold are
much lower than those associated with a 0.25 threshold. For most
combinations of k-values and topologies, increased canalyzing depth leads to
higher distance ratios.
